Now let me rephrase my dream, just so you truly understand my goal...(also thanks so much for still reading!).   *FLASHBACK NARRATION SCENE OF ME AS A LITTLE KID*  I had a rough childhood. My father hurt me and my mom for 13 crappy years, crazy right? It finally shook my mom and she left, but I loved my dad still so much I stayed even though it totally sucked because he'd constantly hurt me, and I don't want to get too detailed because, well, kids might be reading-- anyways, that plus I was always outcasted from my classmates in school and I was pretty much stuck watching Netflix and eating to have fun at the time. It was always hard for me to see the bright side of things and I was losing hope as I sunk deep in to a sort of young depression. That is until I found something.. So I had never really watched Youtube at the time and I thought it was kind of boring tbh. But I was crying that day and looking for enjoyment. Then it was on the screen. "Markiplier's Let's Play Slender The Arrival!" I was so excited because *I LOVED* Slenderman so much, so with that in mind I clicked, not knowing what was to happen...but what would happen, would change my life forever. *(Hey just another thumbs up for still reading!! I know it's a lot sorry!!).*   As I watched Markiplier, as I listened to his positive glow and saw his bright booming smile as he squealed at different things about the game. I noticed something starting to change. I had stopped crying. I was also now smiling, focused and laughing at the video! Ever since then I kept watching his videos *WHENEVER* I was down, or sad or unhappy. His videos never failed to lift me up and cleanse me of my darkness. As he wandered down dark corners bravely, I wandered with him. Like a family. I wanted to share this feeling of happiness. This feeling of peace even in chaos! I wanted anyone like me to see this so that they would be happy too, so that we could all be positive and for once have some sort of universal truth of peace and a wonderful family. I want to do what he does. I want to make YOU smile when no one else is. YOU laugh on a bad day. and YOU can be my family when yours isn't there for you. *(SORRY I'LL HURRY THIS UP! Dang you still reading? wow!)*   So, my dream is to be what Markiplier was to me. A light in a person's darkness. I just want to make everyone laugh and bring everyone together. So that's why I made my Youtube. *TakeTheJurny,* because life is a Journey. Now I just want to say that this is not spam, this is a choice. No one has to sub I just wanted everyone to have a chance to see my Youtube before it hits 1million, and that will happen one day :) thanks for reading, and as always I will see you, when I heed the call, to the next Journey, Adios guys! <3 and thanks so much for reading!!!!   (PS- I've noticed alot of comments think that I'm begging for subs. Not at all ^-^ merely allowing more possibilities to people and myself. If you do not like my content and desire to subscribe that is your choice and I'm fine with that ^.^) :)

text: My name is Dr. William Ferraiolo. I have twenty five years of experience teaching, researching, and publishing articles in academic journals. I have authored a book which contains a collection of meditations in the Stoic tradition that I believe would be an excellent addition to your personal or institutional library. This collection is unique in that each meditation is presented in the second person, encouraging the reader to examine their struggles and failures in the pursuit of self-improvement and enlightenment. The following is a sample meditation that illustrates this:  “Everything that can suffer, does suffer. Everything that can die, will die. You have suffered, you will suffer much more, and a lifetime of your suffering will culminate in your death. When you can muster genuine gratitude for all of that, then you will have made the kind of progress that is not easily reversed. To develop sincere appreciation for this opportunity to be born in a brutal world, not of your making, to struggle and fail time and time again, to feel repeatedly lost, bewildered, frustrated, and hopeless, to swim in this ocean of misery, and, ultimately, to drown in it—this is the beginning of wisdom. You must embody overwhelming gratitude for the opportunity to fail repeatedly, with no guarantee of eventual success, and to wade cheerfully into a doomed struggle against time and your own limitations. You clamber toward your own death across a landscape of thorns, broken glass, and the corpses of those who have gone before you. Would you have it any other way?”  You can purchase my book through Amazon (see link below): https://www.amazon.com/gp/aw/d/1785355872/ref=tmm_pap_title_0?ie=UTF8&qid=1510265657&sr=8-1#featureBulletsAndDetailBullets_secondary_view_div_1527522634362  Thank you for your consideration, Dr. William Ferraiolo

text: That was a really good jump scare right there. I was expecting the one in the hallway to like lurch forward or something but was not expecting the blindside to come rushing in.  What I really like about this movie franchise is that they recognize the way certain poltergeist and demons may act. Like they don't necessarily do jump scares just to make the audience scream, they have a purpose and reason for the entities to act in the way they do. Like in the Annabelle Creation movie, the demon who tormented the girls could have had them probably on the first night but the way the cinematographers treat their antagonists is like they are a character of their own, even if they are creations from a different dimension.   Really cool because they don't seem to just put on a scary mask and be like, "jump out of the closet". They know that for the most part, the audience is tired of cheap scare tactics. We want to be terrified like the first time we saw The Exorcist or Poltergeist. I may or may not see this movie though haha

Jump scares aren’t scary. It’s human nature to jump when there is a loud noise projected in a movie; and it destroys all the tension immediately. I’m not completely against jump scares, but at this point, they have become SO predictable and monotonous that it’s just cheap.

text: its kind of hard for me to get creeped out by this stuff anymore because I feel like none of these movies have any subtlety or mood whatsoever besides "dark room, prepare for jumpscare". My expectations are never messed with and everything's so predictable and methodical and that ruins the creep factor for me. If you show the scary thing too much as well, it stops being scary. We all knew what the nun looks like way before this comes out. She screams, grabs people, shows sharp teeth.. Even the james wan-esque camera tricks are so predictable. The camera is doing a pendulum thing, well then I know when the camera comes back Spooky Figure A is going to be silently standing behind person B and then WAAAAH. And then move onto next scene. All scares are control V'd from the conjuring series with new ghosts... Idk. They're fine but they're not scary anymore. Not if you watch any amount of horror that is. Most horror doesn't scare horror fans so I can't complain much, I'm just desensitized. But cmon, at least give me more mystery or something

text: Warner Bros. has released an unsettling first trailer for “The Nun,” with the demonic sister from “The Conjuring 2” returning to terrorize Taissa Farmiga’s novitiate at a remote convent.  The footage starts with a woman’s voiceover describing her visions of an evil nun, followed by a gravel-voiced sister asserting, “The abbey has a long history — not all of it good.”  The trailer concludes with the young nun walking through the dark – not aware that she’s being followed by the evil nun, who then leaps out. The trailer concludes, “Pray for forgiveness.”  The official synopsis: “When a young nun at a cloistered abbey in Romania takes her own life, a priest with a haunted past and a novitiate on the threshold of her final vows are sent by the Vatican to investigate. Together they uncover the order’s unholy secret. Risking not only their lives but their faith and their very souls, they confront a malevolent force in the form of the same demonic nun that first terrorized audiences in ‘The Conjuring 2,’ as the abbey becomes a horrific battleground between the living and the damned.”  The Nun trailer releases alongside  "Tag"  "Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom" "Unfriended: Dark Web" "The Darkest Minds" In Cinemark Locations "The Meg" In AMC Theaters & Canada Locations  & "Mile 22"   if you saw this trailer Read the replies below

text: Horror movies these days suck. They rely soley on jumpscares and shit, no real tension, just waiting for the next “suprise”. A perfect example of actual fear, and tension, would be FNAF 4. Ik its not a movie, but supposedly will be soon. In game, u must get to the doors, one each on left and right, and in doing so must listen for the breathing of the animatronics, all of which are there to kill you. You must also listen to the footsteps, which signify them moving from door to door. This puts you under extreme pressure, and the anticipation, the quiet that is either followed by breathing, or getting jumpscared. And the fact that they look nightmarish makes it even more terrifying. And thats the thing. With these movies, there is nothing before the jumpscare to show you’re in trouble, or safe.Nothing to add tension, whereas FNAF 4 has that tension.

text: As frightening as the "The Nun" is, it doesn't hold a candle to today's real-life horrors in the Catholic Church.  But while a new generation of filmmakers has breathed new life into horror by embedding it with frightful and salient social commentary, the "The Conjuring" franchise — of which "The Nun" is a spinoff and the fifth installment — isn't about anything so real. It's about exhuming classic horror archetypes — creaky old houses and creepy old dolls — with (mostly) old-school effects. And what's more old school than a mean ol' nun?  Set in 1952, "The Nun" is the origin story of Valak (Bonnie Aarons), a demonic nun who first turned up in "Conjuring 2," as the pursuit of Vera Farmiga's paranormal expert. This time, our protagonist is Sister Irene (played by Vera's younger sister Taissa Farmiga), a novitiate who, just before her vows, is dispatched by the Vatican, along with Father Burke (Demian Bichir), an expert in unexplained phenomena (or as he says, "miracle hunting"), to a remote Romanian abbey where a young nun has just hung herself.  The decaying, overgrown abbey and its adjoining covenant are suitably eerie. The place, handsomely crafted by production designer Jennifer Spence, has the feel of a horror-movie set, complete with a foggy cemetery, and the action that follows has the almost comforting pattern of surprises and scares that's to be expected. Entering the gothic world of "The Nun," built so sturdily on horror movie clichés, is to slide into a darkly fantastical realm that's practically cozy it's so familiar.  Crypts will turn into traps, apparitions will flicker in the mirrors and ancient Christian dogma will be used for all its sinister power. Certainly, anyone who goes anywhere at any time clutching a lantern will run into trouble.  But what distinguishes "The Nun" is its silky, sumptuous shadows. Directed by British filmmaker Corin Hardy ("The Hallows") and shot by Maxime Alexander (who was also cinematographer on the "Conjuring" spinoff "Annabelle: Creation," ''The Nun" shrouds itself so much in darkness that it at times verges on becoming a nightmarish abstraction. You almost lose sense of what exactly is going on, as Sister Irene falls into a labyrinthine abyss.  The spell, of course, gets broken as the demands of plot and franchise return. And "The Nun" has little to offer beyond: Beware of spooky Romanian abbeys. But for a moment or two, it hangs suspended in a luxurious gloom, the kind that these days passes for a welcome escape.  "The Nun," a Warner Bros. release, is rated R by the Motion Picture Association of America for terror, violence, and disturbing/bloody images. Running time: 96 minutes. Three stars out of four.  ___  MPAA definition of R: Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian.  ___  Follow Jake Coyle on Twitter at: http://twitter.com/jakecoyleAP  Jake Coyle, The Associated Press

text: SPOILER ALERT  I had very high hopes before watching this movie. Loved the Conjuring 2 and the depicture of Valak in that movie really gave me the chills. Therefore I was very hyped when I learned about the fact that there would be a whole movie devoted to Valak. I could not have been more wrong while The Nun was very disapointing.  The script felt like a joke to me. So called "scary moments" became laughable thanks to walking dead-like special effects and horrible zombie screaming. Although there were a couple of nicely build up jump scares, I never experienced the feeling of fear. The attempt of putting comedy in some really strange parts did not help either. I find all of this such a shame because The Nun had great potential. For the ones who have not watched this overhyped movie: do not get your hopes up too high!

text: In 1952 Romania, two nuns living at the Cârța Monastery are attacked by an unseen presence while searching for an "artifact". The surviving nun, Sister Victoria, flees from the attacker and jumps out of a window, hanging herself, as the attacker, a demonic entity dressed as a nun, appears outside her room. Her body is discovered the next morning by Frenchie, a man living in a nearby village and tasked with transporting supplies to the nuns, despite never actually seeing them.  The Vatican learns of the incident and dispatches troubled priest Father Burke to investigate along with young novitiate Sister Irene. The pair travels to Romania and meets with Frenchie who leads them to the abbey. At the abbey they discover that Sister Victoria's body has inexplicably moved from where Frenchie originally moved it, fresh blood appears where she was initially found, and a strange key on her body. Entering the chapel outside the abbey, they find themselves unable to enter the actual abbey and encounter the abbess, who informs them that the nuns are having a vow of silence for the night but they can return the next day, offering lodging at the nearby convent. Frenchie is attacked by a possessed nun corpse as he returns to the village, but manages to escape. Irene mentions how she has various visions including that of a nun. Additionally, Burke reveals that a boy he exorcised was fatally injured during the exorcism and has been grieving ever since. The demonic entity terrorizes the pair that night and Burke is rescued by Irene after being trapped in a coffin. They discover to their horror that the coffin is filled with several books about the occult.  The next day, Irene and Burke return to the abbey but only the former can enter as it is cloistered. She meets some of the other nuns and learns that they are praying constantly, swapping in shifts to keep evil at bay. One of the nuns, Sister Oana, reveals the abbey's history: it was built as a castle by a duke who was obsessed with the occult and the dark arts during the Dark Ages. The duke summoned a demonic entity via a rift he opened in the catacombs but was killed by Vatican troops who captured the castle and sealed the rift with an artifact that contains the "blood of Jesus Christ" before Valak could fully emerge. The effects of the bombings during the Second World War caused the rift to open again, unleashing the same entity, which has taken the form of a nun and whom several nuns have spotted at night. Meanwhile, in the chapel, Burke identifies the entity as Valak after reading the books from the coffin and discovers the abbess's body is being controlled by demonic forces who shift into the boy he exorcised.  In the village, Frenchie discovers that the evil from the abbey is plaguing the village after learning of the suicide of a young girl, and decides to head back to the abbey to try and save Irene and Burke. Irene is attacked by Valak and experiences more visions that night. She enters the main part of the abbey where several nuns start to pray to fend off Valak. The group is attacked, suffering large casualties and a demonic force carves a pentagram into Irene's skin. Hearing the chaos, Burke tries to enter the abbey to save Irene but is attacked by a possessed nun corpse. He is saved by a shotgun-wielding Frenchie and the pair enter the abbey to rescue Irene. Upon reaching Irene, the group discovers that none of the nuns were real and they were all visions from Irene. They also learn that Sister Victoria was the last nun alive and had actually hung herself to stop Valak from possessing her body and spreading evil.  Theorizing that Valak can only be stopped if they seal the damaged rift with the blood, the trio enter the catacombs and retrieve the blood vial with the key Sister Victoria had before searching for the rift. The group is attacked and separated by Valak and the ghosts of the dead nuns. Irene is lured into a pentagram and possessed by Valak. Frenchie uses some of the blood to free her. Valak emerges, incapacitating Frenchie and throwing Irene into a flooded chamber that contains the actual rift. Burke is wounded by the ghost of the boy who died as Valak starts to drown Irene. As Valak inspects Irene's body, she spits the blood at the demon, banishing it before using the blood to seal the rift. After Frenchie rescues and resuscitates Irene, he reveals his real name as Maurice to Irene and the trio leave the abbey. However, Maurice is revealed to be partially possessed by Valak via injuries he sustained during the fight.  Twenty one years later at a university seminar, Carolyn Perron watches footage of the Warrens attempting to exorcise Maurice. Maurice touches Lorraine, giving her visions of Ed dying, which initiate the Warrens investigation the Perron household haunting, as well as their encounter with Valak itself  Credit : Wikipedia

text: SPOILERS AHEAD   tl;dr Please, save your money. This movie isn't worth the paper my ticket was printed on.   I was excited for this movie for months. I've been following The Conjuring franchise for a good few years now, and this movie is by far the worst of the lot. I mean, we're approaching bottom of the barrel levels of storytelling, cinematography, and character development. I didn't care about any of the characters, the demon's backstory was not properly fleshed out, and it doesn't follow any kind of logical sequence. If I had to compile a list of movies whose final acts absolutely destroyed what was otherwise a near flawless movie franchise, Star Wars Episode I would take up the 10th spot, and The Nun would take up the other nine.   There is absolutely no build up to the awfully orchestrated horror set pieces, and right at the outset, our (SPOILER ALERT) intrepid Vatican Rambo get his arse dragged from bed and right into a literal coffin. And then our innocent, virginal but I've not yet taken my vows not-yet-nun manages to dig him up in a few minutes. And just in time too, because believe it or not, a pair of horror movie prop hands were clawing at Father Rambo's face (like it was actually going to drag him to a place that was even smaller and inaccessible than that damned coffin he magically found himself in).  I mean(SPOILER ALERT) towards the end of the movie, the demon got a face full of the blood of Christ which is supposed to have killed it, and the climax shows it being destroyed and falling back into hell... but oh, wait let us conveniently also possess the world's most out of place comedic relief and use him as the line that threads all the way back to the Warrens.   And the worst of it all, is that this movie actually had glimpses of plot mechanisms and little details that could have been absolutely amazing. I really liked the idea of those little grave bells. It could have been deployed to so much better effect in my opinion. Also, the not yet nun should have had a far more central role in the story. It feels like her character was originally written so as to be somehow directly connected to the demon, only for the script to have then been taken over and finished by a team of highly trained monkeys. What a waste of highly trained monkeys.   The Conjuring franchise had me believing that silver screen horror still has a place in the world. I still believe this by the way, but not because of The Nun. It is because of Toni Collette's masterful turn in the movie Hereditary. If you want a richly told horror movie that pushes all the right buttons and scares the crap out of you, then THIS is the movie to watch instead. In fact, in a year filled with yet more mindless superheroes and been-there-done-thats, Hereditary is a breath of fresh air. Or it would be, had Toni Collette not scared the breath out of me as she (SPOILER ALERT) crawled through her son's bedroom wall.   But, if like me, you're crazy about horror in all mediums, then for a far superior religiously driven horror story (as compared to The Nun, that is), creepy cinematography, amazingly fleshed out characters, and all the blood and gore you can stomach, I would heartily recommend that you play Outlast 2.   Believe me when I say that the only good thing about The Nun is that YouTube jump scare ad that eventually got banned. At least that's still free.   DO NOT SPEND MONEY ON THIS GARBAGE.

text: The Conjuring (Korku Seansı) ile başlayan dehşet verici ve sürükleyici korku filmi serisinin son ayağı olan The NUN - Dehşetin Yüzü, Türkiye'de 21 Eylül'de bekleyenleri ile buluştu.  Özellikle sosyal medyaya tam bir sır gibi servis edilen, yalnızca bir fragmanı yayınlanan ve ses efektlerinin korkunçluğu dolayısı ile Youtube başta olmak üzere video sitelerinden tek fragman haricinde kaldırıldığı söylentisi ile reklamı yapılan The NUN, izleyiciden geçer not almadı.  The Conjuring, 2013 yılına damga vuran korku filmi olarak tarih yazmıştı. IMDB'de 370.555 oydan toplamda 7.5 oy oranına sahip olmuş, 318,000,141 dolarlık gişe hasılatı ile de kalitesini kanıtlamıştı.  Ardından 2016 yılında The Conjuring 2 - Korku Seansı 2 adıyla filmin daha eski versiyonu gişeye çıktı. Özellikle filmin sonu ile beklentileri karşılamayan ikinci filmde, 320,270,008 dolar gişe hasılatı, ilk filmin kalitesi nedeniyle izlemek isteyenlerin çok olmasına bağlandı.  Sosyal medyada en çok korkutacağı vurgulanan filmin 3. ayağı olan ve şeytan rahibenin ortaya çıkışını konu alan film ise, baştan sona tam bir fiyasko oldu.  İzleyicinin korkmadığı, sadece ani ses efektleri ile birkaç sahnede seyirciyi germeye çalışmış olan yapım, gerek makyaj, gerekse de konunun hafifliği ve filmin sonunun basitliği ile korku filminden uzak kaldı.  Çekimlerin çok karanlık olması ise, göz yormaktan öteye geçemedi. 96 dakikalık filmin neredeyse 80 dakikası karanlıkta neler olduğu anlamak için gözlerinizi yormanıza neden oldu.  Neticede filmden çıkanların mutsuzluğu gerek yüzlerinden gerekse sosyal medyadaki haklı tepkilerinden çok da zor olmadan anlaşılabiliyor.   6 Eylül'de Amerika'da gösterime giren film, ülkemizde ilk kez 21 Eylül'de sinemalarda yayınlandı. Boxoffice verilerine göre ise bugüne kadarki toplam hasılatı ise 93.600.307  dolar.  300milyon dolar bandına yaklaşabileceğine ihtimal verilmeyen film, IMDB'de sadece 5.8 puan alarak hakettiği orta sınıf film listesindeki yerini almış oldu.

It’s hard to explain haha. Which was really good because it made u enjoy it and and be scared at the same time. I did not expect this from theses creators considering there other movies like the conjuring where really serious movies, and did not have comedy in it. I don’t know why some people are hating on it. It’s a really good movie! Yea there are some Parts that are not perfect but that’s ok. It is still really scary and will make u Jump!!  It’s really fun to watch. Great movie, if ur some one who does not want a serious scary movie and want a some humour this is great....let’s also mention  Frenchie was hella relatable... haha  The only parts I did not like is when they showed the demons and shit to much, it made it less scary in those scenes and the Jesus blood bullshit was could have been replaced with something more believable but meh.
